# 🏷 Step 1: Bean Instantiation

Spring creates the Bean object.

Example:

```java id="bl3"
@Component
public class Student {

}
```

The Spring Container creates the object automatically.

---

# 🏷 Step 2: Dependency Injection

Spring injects required dependencies.

```java id="bl4"
@Component
class Engine {

}

@Component
class Car {

    private final Engine engine;

    public Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }

}
```

---

# 🏷 Step 3: Aware Interfaces

Spring provides additional information to Beans.

Common Aware Interfaces:

* BeanNameAware
* BeanFactoryAware
* ApplicationContextAware

Example:

```java id="bl5"
public class Student
implements BeanNameAware {

    @Override
    public void setBeanName(
            String name) {

        System.out.println(name);

    }

}
```

---

# 🏷 Step 4: @PostConstruct

Executed immediately after dependency injection.

```java id="bl6"
import jakarta.annotation.PostConstruct;

@Component
public class Student {

    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        System.out.println(
            "Bean Initialized"
        );
    }

}
```

### Output

```text id="bl7"
Bean Initialized
```

---

# 🏷 Step 5: InitializingBean

The `afterPropertiesSet()` method is called after all properties are injected.

```java id="bl8"
import org.springframework.beans.factory.InitializingBean;

@Component
public class Student
implements InitializingBean {

    @Override
    public void afterPropertiesSet() {

        System.out.println(
            "afterPropertiesSet Called"
        );

    }

}
```

---

# 🏷 Step 6: Custom Init Method

You can define your own initialization method.

```java id="bl9"
@Bean(initMethod = "start")
public Student student() {
    return new Student();
}
```

```java id="bl10"
public class Student {

    public void start() {
        System.out.println(
            "Custom Init Method"
        );
    }

}
```

---

# 🏷 Step 7: Bean Ready

The Bean is fully initialized and available for use.

```text id="bl11"
Spring Container
        │
        ▼
Bean Ready
        │
        ▼
Application Uses Bean
```

---

# 🏷 Step 8: @PreDestroy

Executed before the Bean is destroyed.

```java id="bl12"
import jakarta.annotation.PreDestroy;

@Component
public class Student {

    @PreDestroy
    public void destroy() {

        System.out.println(
            "Bean Destroyed"
        );

    }

}
```

---

# 🏷 Step 9: DisposableBean

Spring calls the `destroy()` method.

```java id="bl13"
import org.springframework.beans.factory.DisposableBean;

@Component
public class Student
implements DisposableBean {

    @Override
    public void destroy() {

        System.out.println(
            "DisposableBean Destroy"
        );

    }

}
```

---

# 🏷 Step 10: Custom Destroy Method

Custom cleanup method.

```java id="bl14"
@Bean(destroyMethod = "stop")
public Student student() {
    return new Student();
}
```

```java id="bl15"
public class Student {

    public void stop() {
        System.out.println(
            "Custom Destroy Method"
        );
    }

}
```

---

# 📊 Complete Bean Lifecycle Example

```java id="bl16"
@Component
public class Student {

    public Student() {
        System.out.println(
            "Constructor Called"
        );
    }

    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        System.out.println(
            "Bean Initialized"
        );
    }

    @PreDestroy
    public void destroy() {
        System.out.println(
            "Bean Destroyed"
        );
    }

}
```

### Output

```text id="bl17"
Constructor Called

Bean Initialized

Application Running

Bean Destroyed
```

